    "Classic phenylketonuria is caused by deficient phenylalanine hydroxylase (or its cofactor tetrahydrobiopterin, BH4), blocking conversion of phenylalanine to tyrosine. Phenylalanine accumulates, causing intellectual disability, seizures, a musty odor, and hypopigmentation (tyrosine becomes essential, limiting melanin). Aspartame is metabolized to phenylalanine, which is exactly why diet-soda and sugar-free-gum labels warn phenylketonurics; treatment is dietary phenylalanine restriction (avoiding aspartame) with tyrosine supplementation, and BH4-responsive forms exist.",
